      "doi": "10.1029/2025jg009321",
      "title": "Greenhouse Gas Dynamics From Created Wetlands of New Brunswick and Nova Scotia (Canada)",
      "authors": [
        "R. Plant",
        "M. Bogard",
        "W. Ampuero‐Reyes",
        "C. N. Chan",
        "G. Chmura"
      ],
      "journal": "Journal of Geophysical Research: Biogeosciences",
      "publication_date": "2026-05-01",
      "abstract": "\n \n Beginning in the 17th century, Acadian settlers dyked and drained salt marshes along the Bay of Fundy in Eastern Canada, transforming them into agricultural fields. Over the last ∼50 years, impoundments were created by building dykes to contain freshwater. Underlain with agricultural soils developed from tidal marsh sediments, these impoundments are potentially unique wetlands. Assessment of their value as Natural Climate Solutions, that is, their impact on climate, requires whole ecosystem carbon budgets, including measurement of greenhouse gas fluxes from their waters. This study examined 5 impoundments, ranging in age from 15 to 56 years. They are primarily fed by precipitation, and water levels are maintained with weirs. Greenhouse gas fluxes were measured in the open water areas of the impoundments using the headspace equilibrium method and bubble traps, for diffusive and ebullitive fluxes, respectively. Sampling occurred monthly from August to November 2024, and in February 2025 (beneath the ice). Total CH\n 4\n and diffusive CO\n 2\n fluxes ranged from −0.3 to 144 and ‐175 to 937 mmol m\n −2\n d\n −1\n , respectively. Diffusive N\n 2\n O fluxes ranged from −77 to −0.3 μmol m\n −2\n d\n −1\n . Approximately 58% of CH\n 4\n emissions were ebullitive, likely due to multiple potential mechanisms influencing CH\n 4\n production and release. Dissolved CH\n 4\n and CO\n 2\n concentrations in the winter were significantly positively related to impoundment age, presumably a result of greater accumulated organic matter in the older impoundments. Additional research on the vegetated parts of the impoundments and the carbon stored in the sediments is needed for final assessment of the impoundments as Natural Climate Solutions.\n",
      "url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/0cdf38426c7bcd4f39bf819cec8aa4a898f56558",
      "pdf_url": "",
