      "source": "Semantic Scholar",
      "pmid": "",
      "doi": "10.59324/ejiss.2026.2(2).15",
      "title": "The Fashion Industry and the UN Sustainable Development Goals",
      "authors": [
        "K. Kotsis"
      ],
      "journal": "European Journal of Innovative Studies and Sustainability",
      "publication_date": "2026-04-13",
      "abstract": "The fashion industry is among the world’s largest contributors to the environmental and social crises that the United Nations’ Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) were adopted to address. Responsible for approximately 8–10% of global greenhouse gas emissions, 93 billion cubic metres of freshwater consumption annually, 92 million tonnes of textile waste, and the employment, under conditions that systematically violate international labour standards, of between 75 and 300 million workers worldwide, the industry’s footprint intersects with the SDG framework at every level. This article provides a systematic review of the fashion industry’s relationship to the 17 SDGs, structured in four analytical clusters: the environmental goals most directly implicated in fashion’s physical flows (SDGs 6, 13, 14, 15); the social and economic goals most directly implicated in its labour and trade structures (SDGs 1, 5, 8); the production and consumption goal that most comprehensively frames the industry’s structural unsustainability (SDG 12); and SDG 4 (Quality Education), which functions as a crosscutting enabler for all others. It further examines the industry’s responses to these obligations, voluntary commitments, certification schemes, and the emerging binding regulatory agenda of the European Union, including the Ecodesign for Sustainable Products Regulation, Extended Producer Responsibility for textiles, and Corporate Sustainability Due Diligence requirements, and critically evaluates their adequacy against the structural accountability gap that persists between commitment and measurable SDG progress. The article argues that a comprehensive response to the fashion-SDG nexus requires not only regulatory and industry-level intervention but the cultivation of fashion literacy, the critical, situated competency to understand the fashion system’s implications and to act as an informed participant within it, as the educational dimension without which structural transformation cannot be democratically sustained.",
