      "doi": "10.1109/IGARSS55030.2025.11244065",
      "title": "Monitoring River Ice and Snow Cover Distribution From Remote Sensing Time-Series and Their Relationship With River Morphology",
      "authors": [
        "Weimeng Xu",
        "Yufan Yang",
        "Hui Shen",
        "Hengyi Zheng",
        "Xiaoguang Shi",
        "Hongjun Su"
      ],
      "journal": "IEEE International Geoscience and Remote Sensing Symposium",
      "publication_date": "2025-08-03",
      "abstract": "River ice has significant impacts on hydrological, ecological, climatic, and socio-economic functions. Seasonal river ice formation plays a crucial role in reducing greenhouse gas emissions from rivers to the atmosphere and serves as a critical indicator of climate change against the backdrop of global warming. Additionally, snow cover on ice indirectly influences the river ice ecosystem. However, due to harsh observational conditions, dense monitoring of river ice phenology remains challenging. The development of remote sensing technologies has enriched the availability of multisource satellite imagery, providing favorable conditions for constructing high-quality spatiotemporal resolution datasets. Despite these advancements, existing studies lack high-resolution spatiotemporal estimation and interannual variability analyses of river ice and snow cover areas. This study integrates multisource optical imagery from the Landsat and Sentinel-2 time series to propose a Multi-Source Snow/Ice Identification Framework (MIS) designed for river applications. The MIS framework enables the calculation of a 30-meter, ten-day scale ice/snow cover area over the Songhua River mainstem (Songyuan city section). Results reveal that over the past six years, the ice period of the Songhua River lasted 108–138 days, with snow cover present during three-quarters of this period. Furthermore, the relationship between river morphology and river ice phenology was analyzed, showing that ice duration exhibited strong correlations with river elevation, width, and sinuosity. Overall, the MIS framework provides an effective methodology for quantifying ice/snow cover during winter. Future work may expand this framework to a global scale, supporting the assessment of cryosphere ecological responses under global change and providing essential data for adaptation strategies.",
      "url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/97f059a15483c20743431558f4360f8fb3d5ec8c",
