      "pmid": "",
      "doi": "10.56899/154.03.19",
      "title": "Tropical Monsoon Climate Influences the Abundance and Vertical Distribution of Methane-oxidizing Bacteria Communities in a Monomictic Lake (Lake Yambo, the Philippines)",
      "authors": [
        "Ryamico Reyes",
        "Sarah Jewel de Leon",
        "Leah Kim Rioflorido",
        "Eunice Grace Rodelas",
        "Alessandra Salengua",
        "Kamille N. Poblete",
        "Iona Eunice C. Bicaldo",
        "Justine R. De Leon",
        "Milette U. Mendoza-Pascual",
        "Eleanor S. Austria",
        "Rey Donne Papa",
        "Noboru Okuda"
      ],
      "journal": "The Philippine journal of science",
      "publication_date": "2025-06-01",
      "abstract": "Methane-oxidizing bacteria (MOB) reduce the amount of natural methane (CH4) emitted by\nfreshwater lakes to the atmosphere, emphasizing their influence on lake CH4 dynamics and their\npotential role in mitigating global warming. The study of CH4 dynamics poses interest in the\ntropical regions as warmer temperatures and climatic factors contribute to higher CH4 production\nand potential emissions. In this study, the abundance and vertical distribution of three MOB\ngroups (Types I and II, and NC10) in the monomictic Lake Yambo (Laguna, the Philippines)\nwere investigated amid monsoonal changes (stratified and mixed states). MOB were quantified\nthrough catalyzed reporter deposition-fluorescence in situ hybridization (CARD-FISH), and\nselect physicochemical parameters (temperature, dissolved oxygen, pH, chlorophyll, and CH4\nconcentration) were measured to determine their impact on MOB abundance. During the lake’s\ncontrasting states, the abundance of MOB communities shifted along the water column with\nsignificant interaction between depth and season, with NC10 (p = 0.02) indicating abundance\nvariation driven by combined spatiotemporal factors. Type I MOB positively correlated with\ntemperature (r = 0.34; p = 0.05) and pH (r = 0.38; p = 0.03), which suggests their preference for\nrelatively warmer and more basic conditions. This study presents the response of MOB to varying\nphysicochemical characteristics brought upon by monsoonal changes, integrating the implications\nof tropical lakes, as potent CH4 sinks, on climate change awareness and lake management.",
