      "doi": "10.1088/1755-1315/1495/1/012005",
      "title": "Evaluation of PET plastic bottles waste’s performance as an evaporation preventer",
      "authors": [
        "S. S. Sah",
        "N. Ishak",
        "W. Ahmad",
        "N. N. Tukimat"
      ],
      "journal": "IOP Conference Series: Earth and Environment",
      "publication_date": "2025-04-01",
      "abstract": "The rapid expansion, and industrial activities in urban areas have resulted in heightened greenhouse gas emissions, contributing to a rise in surrounding temperatures. The alterations have intensified the water cycle, leading to an increase in evaporation from reservoirs such as lakes and rivers. The primary objective of this study is to assess the efficacy of PET (polyethylene terephthalate) plastic bottle waste in preventing evaporation. Further goals involve identifying the ideal surface area for various PET bottle dimensions and establishing a relationship between the evaporation rate and the cover surface area through the application of SPSS software. The study encompasses three treatments that vary in the size of PET bottle caps. Data collection spanned a duration of 2 months, totaling 60 days. The evaporation rate was determined through the application of the Penman Formula Method alongside the experimental data, in addition to a thorough analysis of the water level data across the three treatments for comparative purposes. The findings indicated that PET bottle covers with an 89.57% coverage significantly decreased the evaporation rate when compared to the uncovered control. The investigation revealed a relationship between the evaporation rate and the surface area of the cover, suggesting that PET bottles could serve as a viable approach to reduce water loss from evaporation.",
      "url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/8be104547274bdab2be638aca9c36854c63b36b5",
